# Taygetan Grammar Rules Definition

## Core Sentence Structures

### Word Order Patterns
- OSV (Object-Subject-Verb) - Formal/ritual context
- SOV (Subject-Object-Verb) - Spoken/normal context  
- VSO (Verb-Subject-Object) - Poetic/telepathic context

### Core Grammar Elements
1. Pronouns with case markers
2. Verb conjugations (tense, aspect, mood)
3. Case markers for semantic relationships
4. Consciousness-grade reduplication patterns
5. Particle system for focus and modality

## Grammar Validation Rules

### Case Marking
- Nominative: No marker (default case)
- Accusative: No marker in OSV (default in that structure)
- Genitive: -en (possession)
- Locative: -ra (location/state)
- Instrumental: -sha (means/method)
- Dative: -va (recipient/benefit)
- Ablative: -tan (source/origin)
- Comitative: -ma (accompaniment)

### Tense Markers
- Present: Unmarked
- Past: -an
- Future: -el
- Continuous: -ra
- Perfect: -ta
- Intentive: -es

### Aspect Markers
- Imperfective: -ra
- Perfective: -ta
- Intentive: -es
- Habitual: -na
- Inceptive: -sha
- Cessative: -men
- Potential: -lya

### Consciousness Grade Reduplication
- Grade 1: Base form (individual)
- Grade 2: First syllable reduplication (shared awareness)
- Grade 3: Double reduplication (collective consciousness)
- Grade 4: Triple reduplication (planetary consciousness)
- Grade 5: Quadruple reduplication (solar consciousness)
- Grade 6: Quintuple reduplication (galactic consciousness)
- Grade 7: Sextuple reduplication (universal awareness)